Claimant Count and Universal Credit in Trafford

Claimant Count in Trafford

The Claimant Count indicates the number of people claiming benefits principally for the reason of being unemployed. The Claimant Count in March 2023 was 34.4% higher than in January 2020. The rate of claimants to residents aged 16 to 64 reached 3.2% in March 2023 representing an increment of 0.9% from January 2020. The number of claimants has been decreasing from April 2021 but started to increase again from January 2023.

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford compared to January 2020

The Trafford ward with the largest share of claims in March 2023 was Clifford with 12.9% of all claimants within Trafford. Five wards have more claims in March 2023 compared to March 2022. Sale Moor have the largest reduction in number of claims with 70 less, followed by Stretford (-60), Ashton upon Mersey (-45) and Gorse Hill (-40).

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford's wards

The wards with higher claimant rate in March 2023 were Clifford with 6.8%, Bucklow-St Martins with 6.2%, Gorse Hill with 5.4%. There is a gap of 1.2% between the top five wards on claimant rate and the rest of the wards. The wards where the claimant rate has decreased more from March 2022 to March 2023 are Sale Moor with a decrease in rate of -1.1%, Ashton upon Mersey and Stretford with -0.8% followed by Gorse Hill with -0.5%.

In Trafford from March 2022 to March 2023 all age bands have reduced their claimant count except for the age band 35 to 39 (5 more) and 40 to 44 (35 more). When considering the reduction of claims the age band 25-29 years had the largest reduction with -75 less claims.

Change in the Claimant Count by age bands in Trafford
Change in the Claimant Count by broad age bands in Trafford

At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 already had the highest number of claims, however after the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic which started in March 2020 this figure increased more sharply compared to the other age bands. The claimant rate as a proportion of Trafford’s population within each age band showed then a higher increase in the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34 compared to the others. From January 2023 the count and rate of all age bands have increased.

Almost half of Trafford’s claimants are residents of five of the 21 wards. Almost half of the claimants are under 40 years.

Claimant Count for Trafford's wards by age band

Universal Credit claims in Trafford

The Universal Credit claims in Trafford have increased 82.3% from January 2020 to March 2023. The rate of claims as a proportion of people age 16 to 64 increased form 6.1% to 11.2% from January 2020 to March 2023.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford

The Trafford MSOA with the largest share of claims in March 2023 was Old Trafford with 11.9% of all Universal Credit claims in Trafford. 23 out of the 28 MSOAs have more claims in March 2023 compared to March 2022. The MSOAs with more additional claims when comparing March 2022 to March 2023 were Partington (136), Broadheath & Firsway (117) and Old Trafford (104). The MSOA with more increase in percentage change from March 2022 to March 2023 was Hale Barns with 16% change. The MSOAs with reductions in claims when comparing March 2022 to March 2023 are Sale East (-14), Altrincham East (-9), Sale Central (-8) and Ashton upon Mersey North (-7). The MSOA with more reduction in percentage change from March 2022 to March 2023 was Sale East with -5% change.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford's MSOAs

The MSOAs with higher rates of Universal Credit claims in March 2023 were Partington with 28.4% and Old Trafford with 24.4%. The MSOAs where the rate of Universal Credit claims has increased more from March 2022 to March 2023 were Partington with 2.7% and Broadheath & Firsway with 1.9%. The MSOA where the rate of Universal Credit claims has decreased more from March 2022 to March 2023 was Sale East with -0.3% and and Ashton upon Mersey North with -0.2%.

In Trafford from March 2022 to March 2023 the Over 65 age band has the largest increment in percentage change of Universal Credit claims with 51%. When considering the number of additional claims from March 2022 to March 2023 the 5-year age band 35-39 years had the highest with 247 more claims. The age bands 25-29 and 16-19 have the largest decrease in number of Universal Credit claims. Claimants under 30 decreased in number whilst claimants 30 and over increased in number when comparing March 2022 to March 2023.

Change in the Universal Credit claims by age band for Trafford

Following the start of the Covid-19 pandemic in March 2020 the number of claims for all ages rose dramatically from pre-pandemic levels at a similar proportion for all age bands with the age band 16-24 rising faster in May 2020. At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 had the highest number of claims and also the highest rate maintaining that position after the rise from March 2020 until May 2022 when the 35-44 became the age band with the highest number of claims. The age band 16-24 has the lowest number of claims among the other age bands from July 2021. All the age bands are increasing their number of claims particularly from January 2023.

The Conditionality regimen for entitlement to Universal Credit is associated to work-related things that claimants will have to do to maintain elegibility. In Trafford the largest proportion of Universal Credit claims are in the “No work requirements” category however there is also a significant proportion of claims under “Searching for work”.
